04890nam a22007455i 9780691187594DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911875947 a10.1515/97806911875942doi  a(DE-B1597)501709  a(OCoLC)1076457720  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPA3067b.M35 2001eb 7aHIS0020102bisacsh 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a880.9/35204222300aMaking Silence Speak :bWomen's Voices in Greek Literature and Society /cAndré Lardinois, Laura McClure. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2001  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Illustrations -- tNote on Abbreviations, Texts, and Translations -- tCHAPTER ONE. Introduction / rMcClure, Laura -- tPART ONE: T H E ARCHAIC PERIOD -- tCHAPTER TWO. This Voice Which Is Not One / rWorman, Nancy -- tCHAPTER THREE. The Voice at the Center of the World / rMaurizio, Lisa -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Just Like a Woman / rMartin, Richard P. -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Keening Sappho / rLardinois, André -- tPart Two: THE CLASSICAL PERIOD -- tCHAPTER SIX. Virtual Voices / rBlok, Josine H. -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Antigone and Her Sister(s) / rGriffith, Mark -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Women's Cultic Joking and Mockery / rO'Higgins, D. M. -- tCHAPTER NINE. Women's Voices in Attic Oratory / rGagarin, Michael -- tPart Three: THE LATE CLASSICAL PERIOD AND BEYOND -- tCHAPTER TEN. The Good Daughter / rStehle, Eva -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. Ladies' Day at the Art Institute / rSkinner, Marilyn B. -- tCHAPTER TWELVE. Windows on a Woman's World / rCribiore, Raffaella -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN. (In-)Versions of Pygmalion / rRosenmeyer, Patricia A. -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex  aThis collection attempts to recover the voices of women in antiquity from a variety of perspectives: how they spoke, where they could be heard, and how their speech was adopted in literature and public discourse. Rather than confirming the old model of binary oppositions in which women's speech was viewed as insignificant and subordinate to male discourse, these essays reveal a dynamic and potentially explosive interrelation between women's speech and the realm of literary production, religion, and oratory. The contributors use a variety of methodologies to mine a diverse array of sources, from Homeric epic to fictional letters of the second sophistic period and from actual letters written by women in Hellenistic Egypt to the poetry of Sappho. Throughout, the term "voice" is used in its broadest definition. It includes not only the few remaining genuine women's voices but also the ways in which male authors render women's speech and the social assumptions such representations reflect and reinforce. These essays therefore explore how fictional female voices can serve to negotiate complex social, epistemological, and aesthetic issues. The contributors include Josine Blok, Raffaella Cribiore, Michael Gagarin, Mark Griffith, André Lardinois, Richard Martin, Lisa Maurizio, Laura McClure, D. M. O'Higgins, Patricia Rosenmeyer, Marilyn Skinner, Eva Stehle, and Nancy Worman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aGreek literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aGreek literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen and literaturezGreece. 0aWomenzGreecexIntellectual life. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aLardinois, André, eeditor.1 aMcClure, Laura, eeditor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187594zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187594.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  